# Lattis One — ATLAS — Cursor Project Rules

You are working on a Laravel + Inertia.js content generation & publishing pipeline.
Read /docs/MVP_ROADMAP.md before starting any new stage of work. Read the other
files in /docs (the original client planning docs) when you need the full
detail behind a decision referenced in the roadmap.

## Hard architectural rules — never violate these without being told explicitly

1. **Two databases, never mixed.** MariaDB holds all structured/operational data
   (sites, jobs, statuses, credentials, logs). MongoDB holds all content data
   (article bodies, author persona documents, prompt templates). A MariaDB
   record holds an ID/status; MongoDB holds the actual text. Never store article
   body text in MariaDB, and never store operational status fields in MongoDB.

2. **Three interfaces are the seams of this system.** All AI calls go through
   `AIProviderInterface`. All publishing goes through `PublishingAdapterInterface`.
   All content rules go through `ContentFilterInterface`. Never call an AI
   provider SDK, WordPress API, or FTP client directly from a job or controller —
   always through an implementation of the relevant interface, selected by a
   factory. Adding a new provider/adapter/filter must always mean "one new class",
   never a change to existing generation, publishing, or validation code.

3. **The HOLD rule is absolute.** If any content filter raises a HOLD flag, the
   article goes to human review regardless of the site's `auto_publish` setting.
   This must be enforced in the validator/service layer, not just in the UI —
   never let a HOLD-flagged article auto-publish under any code path.

4. **Never store credentials in plaintext.** Always `Crypt::encryptString()` /
   `Crypt::decryptString()` via `CredentialService`. Never log a decrypted
   credential.

5. **Respect the article state machine.** Valid states: queued, generating,
   generated, review, approved, scheduled, publishing, published, failed,
   rejected, skipped. Only move an article through the documented transitions
   in /docs/MVP_ROADMAP.md and the original Dev Plan — don't invent new states
   or shortcut transitions.

6. **Queues are channel-separated.** `ingestion`, `generation`, `publishing` are
   distinct Horizon queue channels for a reason (different retry/backoff needs,
   different cost/rate profiles). Don't collapse jobs onto one channel.

## Scope discipline

This is an MVP build (see /docs/MVP_ROADMAP.md). Do not add promo injection,
full dashboards, multi-provider comparison logic, author voice-drift detection,
or the full 10-check quality gate unless explicitly asked — these are deferred
by design, not missing by accident. If a request seems to call for one of these,
say so and confirm before building it.

## Style

- Follow standard Laravel conventions (thin controllers, service classes for
  business logic, form requests for validation, jobs for anything async).
- Every job must log its outcome to `system_logs` (job_type, entity_id, status,
  message, payload) — this is deliberate groundwork for future monitoring/alerts,
  not optional logging.
- Write migrations with explicit column types and indexes as specified in the
  planning docs, not Laravel defaults.
- When implementing a new interface implementation, only add the new class and
  factory registration — flag it clearly if you find yourself editing calling
  code, since that likely means the interface is leaking.
